        <OtherAbstract Type="PIP" Language="eng">
            <AbstractText>To determine whether normal balance is restored to the hypothalamic-pituitary-adrenal axis after pregnancy, the dexamethasone suppressibility of plasma cortisol in 7 women 4 days after delivery was compared with that in 15 nonpregnant women (10 of whom who were using oral contraceptives).  The plasma concentrations of cortisol before dexamethasone administration in the postpartum women were not significantly different from those of normal nonpregnant women ingesting estrogen-based oral contraceptives; however, both these groups had higher pre-dexamethasone concentrations of cortisol than the group of normal cycling women not taking oral contraceptives.  Dexamethasone reduced the plasma total in all women, but plasma cortisol after dexamethasone was significantly higher in the postpartum group than in nonpregnant women.  The observed persistence of dexamethasone resistance for at least 4 days after removal of the placenta argues against a glucocorticoid-resistant placental stimlus acting at the level of the adrenal.  Antagonism of glucocorticoid inhibition at the pituitary or hypothalamus by progesterone would also appear to be ruled out by the demonstration of persistence of dexamethasone resistance after pregnancy, at a time when plasma progesterone has returned to nonpregnant levels.  On the other hand, it is possible that progesterone may still occupy cortisol receptors 4 days postpartum.</AbstractText>
        </OtherAbstract>
